Cyclistic Bike-Share

Anh Tran

April 2012

1. Introduction

Welcome to the Cyclistic Bike_Share case study. Cyclistic, a bike-share company in Chicago, features more than 5,800 bikes and 600 docking station. They offer docked bike, classic bike and electric bike. There are two options for bike users: casual and member.

In this study, R has been used to analyse the datasets for the year of 2020. All the data including member type, bike type, time, duration of ride, to name a few are collected. Analyzing all those data will help the Company to better understanding how casual and member rider use Cylistic bikes differently depending on the season of the year or the location.

2. Collecting Data

Cylistics historical trip data of 12 months in 2020 were downloaded from here. All the .csv files were unzip and stored in working directory

3. Wrangling Data

3.1 Setting up environment

Required packages

  • tidyverse for data import, wrangling, and for visualization
  • libridate for date functions

3.2 Importing Data

  • Import all dataset one by one for 12 months in 2020 using function read.csv(). For example: m1 <- read.csv(202001-divvy-tripdata.csv)

3.3 Cleaning Data

  • Check datatype of all columns using str() to ensure the consistence between datasets. For example, start_station_id and end_station_id are integer in some files but are character in others. Thus, those columns in several files have been changed from integer type to character type using as.character() function to ensure consistence in the whole dataset.

  • Merge all the files to the final one for analysis using bind_rows() function. The dataset includes 3,541,683 rows and 13 columns

3.4. Calculating ride_length

  • Add a ride_length calculation to all_trips dataset (in seconds). Further checking whether this datatype is numeric. Otherwise, conversion to numeric is needed. All the calculations are then converted to minutes.
all_trips$ride_length <- difftime(all_trips$ended_at,all_trips$started_at)
is.numeric(all_trips$ride_length) 
## [1] FALSE
all_trips$ride_length <- as.numeric(as.character(all_trips$ride_length))
is.numeric(all_trips$ride_length)
## [1] TRUE
all_trips$ride_length <- all_trips$ride_length/60
  • The dataset is finally check for any negative value of ride_length which is calculated as above. All the negative values are removed. The dataset is now ready for analysis.
all_trips_v2 <- all_trips[!(all_trips$start_station_name == "HQ QR" | all_trips$ride_length<=0),]

4.1 Correlation between number of Rides per Day and Customer Type of Casual or Member

  • Number of rides per day of Member consistently increases from Monday to Friday, and then flat out during the weekend. In contrast, that of casual significantly increases during the weekend.
  • Number of rides per day during weekdays of Member are nearly double that of casual type
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'member_casual'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.

4.2 Correlation between Average Ride Length per Day and Customer Type of Casual or Member

  • Although the number of rides per day of Member is significantly higher than that of Casual rider. However, the duration of ride per day of Casual rider (abput 45 minutes/day) is over two times the time Member rides spend on the bike.
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'member_casual'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.

4.3 Correlation between number of Rides Length and Customer Type of Casual or Member as a function of Month

  • For the Member riders, the average duration peaks in April and the gradually decrease in other months.
  • In contrast, the average duration for Casual riders maximizes in January, follows by February and then fluctuates in other months. It is also observed that the duration of riders in January and February is more than 2 times the other months.
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'member_casual'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.

4.4 Correlation between number of Rides and Customer Type of Casual or Member as a function of Month

  • Although the duration spending on the bike of the Member substantially lower than the Casual riders, their frequency of using bike is much higher. Both number of rides peak in August, follow by September and July and then decreases in other months. January/February and April seem the low season for Casual and Member riders respectively.

5. Conclusions

The dataset of bike riders in 2020 of Cylistic company has been analysed using R. Significant insight into the data has been gained. It was observed that the usage of both casual and member riders change with bike type, time and location. Number of member riders dominant as well as the docked bike type. From all these results, suitable marketing is required to enhance the usage of casual rider as well as proper preparation to make sure that bike is always available at the busiest stations.
